A practical look at the tools and packages behind my full-stack TypeScript monorepo, from API generation and server state to code quality and developer workflow.

8 min read
1 hour ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

A modern full-stack project is not only about choosing a frontend framework and a backend framework.
The real difference comes from the smaller tools around them: how you manage the workspace, keep code clean, connect frontend and backend, handle server state, and avoid duplicating types.
In my terminal-inspired notepad project, I use Next.js and NestJS as the main frameworks, but the supporting packages are what make the workflow feel fast, structured, and scalable.
This article is a quick rundown of the most important packages in the stack, plus two additions I would strongly consider for larger TypeScript projects.
You can explore the complete source code here:
View the GitHub repository
And if you want to build the whole project step by step, including the monorepo, API, database, generated hooks, and AI-assisted workflow:
Check out my Next JS Modern Stack — Tooling and AI course
Bun and Turborepo
Bun manages dependencies and workspaces in this project, while Turborepo coordinates tasks across the frontend and backend.
The root project exposes a few commands that make the full stack easy to run:
{
"scripts": {
"dev": "turbo run dev",
"dev:web": "bun --filter web dev",
"dev:api": "bun --filter api start:dev",
"lint": "biome check .",
"lint:fix": "biome check --unsafe --fix .",
"generate": "turbo run generate"
}
}This gives you a simple workflow:
# Run Next.js and NestJS together
bun run dev# Run only the frontend
bun run dev:web# Run only the API
bun run dev:api# Generate the API client
bun run generateTurborepo does not replace the scripts inside each application. It gives the monorepo one consistent way to run them.
That becomes useful as the project grows and starts to include builds, tests, code generation, and CI workflows.
Biome and Lefthook
Biome is the code-quality tool in this stack.
It replaces the usual ESLint and Prettier combination with one fast tool for linting and formatting.
bun run lintTo automatically apply safe fixes:
bun run lint:fixThe project also uses Lefthook to run checks before commits:
pre-commit:
commands:
lint:
run: "bun run lint:fix {staged_files}"
stage_fixed: trueThis is a small detail, but it makes a real difference.
Instead of hoping that formatting is correct before every commit, the workflow checks staged files automatically. This is especially useful when code is written quickly or generated with AI assistance.
Next.js and React
The frontend is built with Next.js and React.
Next.js handles routing, rendering, and the application structure. React handles interactive UI components.
The project uses a feature-oriented structure inside src/modules, which keeps related UI and logic together instead of placing everything in one large components folder.
For example, the terminal UI lives in its own module:
src/
├── app/
└── modules/
├── shared/
└── terminal/The goal is to keep the app easy to navigate as it gets more features.
Next.js gives the project a strong frontend foundation, but it becomes much more useful when combined with good data fetching and URL state tools.
NestJS
NestJS is the backend framework.
It gives the API a clean module-based structure, decorators for defining routes, dependency injection, and a good integration with Swagger.
A small NestJS controller can look like this:
import { Controller, Get } from "@nestjs/common";
import { ApiOperation, ApiResponse } from "@nestjs/swagger";
import { FolderDto } from "./folder.dto";
import { FoldersService } from "./folders.service";@Controller("folders")
export class FoldersController {
constructor(private readonly foldersService: FoldersService) {} @Get()
@ApiOperation({
summary: "Get all folders",
operationId: "getFolders",
})
@ApiResponse({
status: 200,
description: "List of folders",
type: [FolderDto],
})
async findAll() {
return this.foldersService.findAll();
}
}The controller stays focused on HTTP concerns.
The actual database work belongs in the service layer.
That separation makes backend code easier to test, extend, and reason about.
Prisma
Prisma is the database toolkit used by the NestJS API.
The project uses PostgreSQL, and Prisma defines the database models for folders and notes.
model Folder {
id Int @id @default(autoincrement())
name String
parentId Int?
parent Folder? @relation("FolderToFolder", fields: [parentId], references: [id])
children Folder[] @relation("FolderToFolder")
notes Note[]
createdAt DateTime @default(now())
}model Note {
id Int @id @default(autoincrement())
text String
folderId Int
folder Folder @relation(fields: [folderId], references: [id])
createdAt DateTime @default(now())
}Then, inside a NestJS service, creating a note is simple and fully typed:
create(text: string, folderId: number) {
return this.prisma.note.create({
data: {
text,
folderId,
},
});
}Prisma keeps database code readable and gives you strong TypeScript types without manually writing SQL for every query.
In the course, I use Prisma with PostgreSQL through Neon, including migrations, schema design, and connecting the database to NestJS.
Swagger
Swagger is where the backend becomes the source of truth for the API contract.
NestJS can generate Swagger documentation directly from your controllers and DTOs.
import { DocumentBuilder, SwaggerModule } from "@nestjs/swagger";const config = new DocumentBuilder()
.setTitle("Next Modern Stack API")
.setDescription("API documentation for Next Modern Stack")
.setVersion("1.0")
.build();const document = SwaggerModule.createDocument(app, config);SwaggerModule.setup("api-docs", app, document);This creates interactive API documentation at:
http://localhost:3001/api-docsMore importantly, it also gives the frontend a machine-readable API document.
That is where Orval comes in.
Orval
Orval generates TypeScript API types, request functions, and TanStack Query hooks from the Swagger document.
The frontend configuration is small:
import { defineConfig } from "orval";export default defineConfig({
api: {
input: "http://localhost:3001/api-docs-json",
output: {
target: "./src/generated/api.ts",
client: "react-query",
httpClient: "fetch",
baseUrl: "http://localhost:3001",
},
},
});Then run:
bun run generateNow the frontend receives generated code based on the actual API contract.
This is much better than manually copying request types between the frontend and backend.
When the backend changes, you regenerate the client. The TypeScript compiler can then show you where the frontend needs to be updated.
That is one of my favorite parts of the stack because it reduces repetitive work and prevents frontend-backend mismatches.
TanStack Query
TanStack Query manages server state in the frontend.
It handles fetching, caching, mutations, loading states, refetching, and cache invalidation.
Because Orval generates React Query hooks, the frontend can use the API with very little boilerplate:
import { useQueryClient } from "@tanstack/react-query";
import {
getGetFoldersQueryKey,
useCreateNote,
useGetFolders,
} from "@/generated/api";const queryClient = useQueryClient();const { data: foldersData } = useGetFolders();
const { mutateAsync: createNote } = useCreateNote();async function handleCreateNote(text: string, folderId: number) {
await createNote({
data: {
text,
folderId,
},
}); await queryClient.invalidateQueries({
queryKey: getGetFoldersQueryKey(),
});
}The flow is clear:

• Fetch folders with a generated query hook.

• Create a note with a generated mutation hook.

• Invalidate the folder query.

• TanStack Query fetches fresh data.
You do not have to manually manage cache state or write a custom fetching layer for every endpoint.
nuqs
nuqs is a small but powerful package for synchronizing React state with URL search parameters.
In the terminal app, the selected folder path is stored in the URL:
import { useQueryState } from "nuqs";const [path, setPath] = useQueryState("folder", {
defaultValue: "",
});A folder path can then be saved like this:
setPath([1, 4, 12].join(","));The URL becomes shareable:
/?folder=1,4,12This is useful for more than folder navigation.
You can use the same pattern for:

• search queries

• filters

• pagination

• sorting

• selected tabs

• modal state

• dashboards
Keeping this type of UI state in the URL makes an application easier to share, refresh, debug, and navigate.
Tailwind CSS and classnames
Tailwind CSS keeps styling close to the component.
Instead of maintaining large CSS files for every UI variation, you compose utility classes directly where the component is rendered.
The project also includes classnames for conditional class handling:
import classNames from "classnames";type Props = {
isSelected: boolean;
};export function TerminalItem({ isSelected }: Props) {
return (
<button
className={classNames(
"rounded px-2 py-1 font-mono text-sm",
isSelected
? "bg-green-500 text-black"
: "text-green-500 hover:bg-gray-800",
)}
>
documents
</button>
);
}This is not a complicated package, but it keeps conditional styles readable when components become more interactive.
Two Packages I Would Add: Zod and ts-pattern
The packages above are part of the current project.
These next two are not currently included in the repository, but I would recommend them for many larger TypeScript applications.
Zod for Runtime Validation
TypeScript validates code while you develop.
It does not validate data at runtime.
That matters when data comes from places you do not fully control:

• forms

• URL parameters

• environment variables

• webhooks

• third-party APIs

• local storage

• user-generated content
Zod lets you define a schema once and validate unknown data safely.
import { z } from "zod";const createNoteSchema = z.object({
text: z.string().trim().min(1).max(10_000),
folderId: z.coerce.number().int().positive(),
});const result = createNoteSchema.safeParse({
text: "My new note",
folderId: "5",
});if (!result.success) {
console.error(result.error.flatten());
} else {
console.log(result.data);
// { text: "My new note", folderId: 5 }
}Zod is especially useful on the frontend before submitting a form, or at any external boundary where TypeScript types alone are not enough.
ts-pattern for Safer Conditional Logic
ts-pattern is useful when a large switch statement starts to become hard to read.
It gives you pattern matching with strong TypeScript inference and exhaustive checks.
import { match } from "ts-pattern";type SaveState = "idle" | "saving" | "success" | "error";function getStatusText(state: SaveState) {
return match(state)
.with("idle", () => "Ready to save")
.with("saving", () => "Saving...")
.with("success", () => "Saved")
.with("error", () => "Could not save")
.exhaustive();
}The useful part is .exhaustive().
If you later add another state, TypeScript forces you to handle it.
This works well for:

• request states

• modal states

• notification types

• event handlers

• complex API responses

• discriminated unions
It is not required for every project, but it can make complicated UI logic much easier to understand.
The Stack Is About Workflow, Not Dependency Count
None of these packages are useful just because they are popular.
They work well together because each one has a clear responsibility:

• Bun manages the workspace and scripts.

• Turborepo coordinates work across apps.

• Biome and Lefthook protect code quality.

• Next.js and React power the frontend.

• NestJS structures the backend.

• Prisma manages database access.

• Swagger documents the API.

• Orval generates the frontend client.

• TanStack Query manages server state.

• nuqs keeps UI state in the URL.

• Tailwind and classnames make UI styling practical.

• Zod and ts-pattern are strong additions when runtime validation and complex state logic become important.
The goal is not to install every package.
The goal is to build a workflow
